The `thenApply` stage may run in calling thread if it can be started at time of executing the `thenApply`, otherwise when not completed at that moment it should run in the thread of the preceding executing task.

You can demonstrate with:

    Function&lt;String,String&gt; func = s -&gt; {
        System.out.println(Thread.currentThread()+&quot; &quot;+s);
        return s;
    };

    ExecutorService exec1 = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(4);
    ExecutorService exec2 = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(4);
    Future&lt;String&gt; f = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -&gt; func.apply(&quot;ONE&quot;), exec1)
                             .thenApplyAsync(s -&gt; func.apply(&quot;TWO:&quot;+s), exec2)
                             .thenApply(s -&gt; func.apply(&quot;THREE:&quot;+s));

    System.out.println(&quot;f.get()=&quot;+f.get());

This should print the threads used. If run this a few times you may see alternate handling for step 3. Both thread pools are used for steps 1/2 and if the action is quick either the calling thread is used for step 3 (main in this case).

    Thread[#20,pool-1-thread-1,5,main] ONE
    Thread[#21,pool-2-thread-1,5,main] TWO:ONE
    Thread[#1,main,5,main] THREE:TWO:ONE
    f.get()=THREE:TWO:ONE

or it may print that it used the preceding executor service - as for step 2. 

    Thread[#20,pool-1-thread-1,5,main] ONE
    Thread[#21,pool-2-thread-1,5,main] TWO:ONE
    Thread[#21,pool-2-thread-1,5,main] THREE:TWO:ONE
    f.get()=THREE:TWO:ONE

If you add a `sleep` to the task step, you are likely to see the latter only.

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/util/concurrent/CompletionStage.html#thenApply(java.util.function.Function)

Your code would be executed on the pool you explicitly set, no magic:
```
ExecutorService pool1 = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(1, r -&gt; new Thread(r, &quot;t1&quot;));
ExecutorService pool2 = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(2, r -&gt; new Thread(r, &quot;t2&quot;));

Runnable sleep = () -&gt; {
    try {
        Thread.sleep(100);
    } catch (InterruptedException ignore) {
        Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
    }
};

System.out.println(&quot;Result 1: &quot; + CompletableFuture
    .supplyAsync(() -&gt; {
        return Thread.currentThread().getName();
    }, pool1)
    .thenApply(it -&gt; {
        return it + &quot;, &quot; + Thread.currentThread().getName();
    }).join()
);
System.out.println(&quot;Result 2: &quot; + CompletableFuture
    .supplyAsync(() -&gt; {
        sleep.run();
        return Thread.currentThread().getName();
    }, pool1)
    .thenApply(it -&gt; {
        sleep.run();
        return it + &quot;, &quot; + Thread.currentThread().getName();
    }).join()
);

System.out.println(&quot;Result 3: &quot; + CompletableFuture
    .supplyAsync(() -&gt; {
        return Thread.currentThread().getName();
    }, pool1)
    .thenApplyAsync(it -&gt; {
        return it + &quot;, &quot; + Thread.currentThread().getName();
    }, pool2)
    .join()
);

System.out.println(&quot;Result 4: &quot; + CompletableFuture
    .supplyAsync(() -&gt; {
        sleep.run();
        return Thread.currentThread().getName();
    }, pool1)
    .thenApplyAsync(it -&gt; {
        sleep.run();
        return it + &quot;, &quot; + Thread.currentThread().getName();
    }, pool2)
    .join()
);

pool1.shutdownNow();
pool2.shutdownNow();
```

Output:
```
Result 1: t1, main // OR `Result 1: t1, t1` if you are unlucky enough
Result 2: t1, t1
Result 3: t1, t2
Result 4: t1, t2
```

The only interesting thing here is behaviour of the completed futures. Completed future would NOT pass its executor down the chain, so if pool is not configured explicitly (`Result 1`) chain may run on the current thread.

