If you want to register beans from another jar automatically you have to create your own auto-configuration. Spring Boot checks for the presence of a `META-INF/spring.factories` file within your published jar (Application 2). You should add this file to you `resources` folder in the Application 2. The file should list your configuration classes under the EnableAutoConfiguration key.

Here is example code:

```java
import okhttp3.OkHttpClient;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;

@Configuration
public class OkHttpAutoConfiguration {


    @Bean
    public OkHttpClient defaultOkHttpClient(){
        return new OkHttpClient.Builder().build();
    }
    
}

```

**spring.factories**
```
org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.EnableAutoConfiguration=\
  com.example.client.OkHttpAutoConfiguration
```

